\begin_layout Standard
The model describes how exogenous shocks propagates across the economy at
 each time step (a day in this study).
 Such a shock is defined for a set of industries by the amount of production
 capacity lost and how the model recover from the shock either by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Regaining its production capacity following an exogenous recovery function
 governed by a characteristic time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\textrm{recover}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Via the endogenous answer to a rebuilding demand.
 In this case, industries answer the remaining rebuilding demand at each
 step at a rate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\tau_{\textrm{rebuild}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following a shock, the imbalance between production and demand is resolved
 by a proportional rationing scheme, which then leads clients of affected
 industries (both industries and households) to not receive the totality
 of their orders.
 Industries can buffer these unfilled orders with their inventories of inputs
 and increase their resupply demand, possibly shifting to other suppliers.
 Currently, households simply register the loss as final consumption not
 met.
 During the simulation, industries adjust their production and orders based
 on total demand.
 When total demand is higher than current production, industries can increase
 their output at a characteristic rate of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\displaystyle \frac{1}{\tau_{\textrm{alpha}}}}$
\end_inset

 up to a maximum overproduction factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\textrm{max}}$
\end_inset

.
 In ARIO, overproduction comes at no cost for the economic agents: it is
 limited by the fact that it is not an instantaneous process and that it
 cannot exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\textrm{max}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Production level is also constrained by the state of inventories.
 At a given step, inventory size of an input is defined as the number of
 days that an industry can sustain its current production level without
 receiving additional supplies.
 Therefore, inventory goals are set relative to the initial inventory values
 as well as the current production capacity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notably, if the inventory of an input appears insufficient to maintain the
 current production level for a goal duration, an industry will enter 
