\begin_layout Subsubsection
Overproduction pace
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsubsec421"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This parameter determines how an industry can ramp up its production when
 there is a higher demand than the current production level.
 It is a measure of the time it takes for the industry to respond to the
 scarcity of goods.
 The magnitude of this parameter is linked to a scarcity index, meaning
 that as the gap between production and demand widens, the industry accelerates
 its overproduction at a faster pace (See 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app1.1.2 overprod"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most common value for this parameter in the recent literature is 365
 days 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "guan20_global_suppl_chain_effec_covid_contr_measur,koks14_integ_direc_indir_flood_risk_model,hallegatte13_model_role_inven_heter_asses"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which implies that it takes approximately one year for the industry to
 reach maximum overproduction.
 Previous studies used a value of half a year 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ranger10_asses_poten_impac_climat_chang,hallegatte08_adapt_region_input_output_model,wu11_region_indir_econom_impac_evaluat_wench_earth"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We broaden the range of values for this parameter by including faster and
 slower pace, hence testing the four following values: 90 days, 180 days,
 365 days, and 530 days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inventory heterogeneity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsubsec422"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we describe in Section
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec32"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 parameter governs how industries consider the state of their inventory
 of inputs sufficient for their current level of production.
 If we distinguish between industry level (branches) and firms that compose
 them, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 can also be thought of as the degree of heterogeneity and possible substitution
 between firms belonging to an industry:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is close to 0, an inventory reduction in an industry is homogeneously distribut
ed among its firms: inventory reduction impacts industry production only
 if its large enough to affect a sufficiently large part of the firms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is close to 1, an inventory reduction in an industry is concentrated in
 a few firms and forces them to stop producing which directly impact production
 on the industry level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hallegatte13_model_role_inven_heter_asses"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 evaluates his model sensitivity to 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 on five different values: 0.5, 0.7, 0.8 0.9 and 1 and shows the model to be
 highly sensitive to this parameter.
 As 0.5 and 0.7 values show no forward propagation of the initial shock, we
 assume evaluating for a lower value is not necessary.
 Moreover, in the same study, he suggests that for the case of a region
 being affected in a large economy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 would tend to be larger.
 Hence, in our analysis, we investigate the effects of the following 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 values: 0.5, 0.8, 0.85, 0.90, 0.95, 0.97 and 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Recovery/Rebuilding scenario
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsubsec423"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also consider two options for recovery of destroyed productive capital:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Recovery case
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Exogenous linear recovery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Rebuilding case
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Endogenous recovery through the answer to a rebuilding demand equal to
 the direct damages
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app1.1.2 shock"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and supplementary materials for details on how this demand is distributed
 among sectors
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We compare these two cases, as both exist in the literature (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wang20_econom_footp_calif_wildf"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "koks14_integ_direc_indir_flood_risk_model"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), and to our knowledge, no study exists that compares both scenarios.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, natural disasters can affect production capacity only temporarily
 without requiring productive capital to be rebuilt.
 As well, the need for rebuilding, when required, may not be strictly equivalent
 to the direct damages, as some destroyed elements may not be reconstructed.
 Our two scenarios provide insights on how considering a rebuilding demand
 or not affect results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both cases, we also evaluate the sensitivity to the temporal dimension
 of the recovery process.
 We consider multiple characteristic periods
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the recovery case, a characteristic period of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{recover}$
\end_inset

 days means that productive capital is recovered in approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{recover}$
\end_inset

 days (depending on the recovery curve).
 For the rebuilding case, it means that 
\begin_inset Formula ${1}/{\tau_{rebuilding}}$
\end_inset

 of the remaining rebuilding demand is ordered at each step.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ranging from three months to two years.
 For the recovery case (no rebuilding demand) we also consider the sensitivity
 to the shape of the recovery curve (linear or S-shaped).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we do not make any assumptions about the likelihood or validity
 of the considered scenarios for the chosen case study.
 Rather, this study serves as a theoretical exploration of the sensitivity
 of the economic model to different recovery and rebuilding scenarios.
\end_layout

