\begin_layout Standard
Building agent-based models such as ARIO requires a trade-off between the
 simplicity of the mechanisms described and the amount of parameters to
 calibrate, and therefore the transparency of modeled impacts.
 Considering both the conceptual model or its implementation, several hypotheses
 are made, leading to important limits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Hypotheses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "app1.3.1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Production is Leontief-based: no substitution possible between different
 inputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Goods produced in the same sector but in different locations are perfect
 substitutes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Industries can always hire (for overproduction).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Industries and households can always buy goods (no prices, no wages, no
 budget).
\end_layout

